<p>Now, as the first parents are not here counted, not surviving the first century, nor even their youngest calf living through the second, in the third at least the regular birth and death rates must be established. The number alive after two centuries, we see, is but 17 times that at the end of the first; while the number alive after three centuries is 21 times those surviving the second. But a 21-fold increase per century is doubling in every 22.7 years; for as Log. 31 is to 100, so is Log. 2 to 22.7. This rate will give in 5 centuries about 2,400,000 elephants, and in one more century 50,000,000. Even the second century’s 17-fold increase would approach Mr. Darwin’s first results. His present correction, therefore, allowing not even an 8-fold centurial increase, must, I think, involve some great error.</p>
<p>E<hi rend="smallCaps">dward</hi> L. G<hi rend="smallCaps">arbett</hi></p> 
